<HEADLINE>
DPP CHAIRMAN SIGNS TAIWAN FUTURE CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kaohsiung,  April 23 (CNA) 04/23/07  20:19:05 (By Elizabeth Hsu)
</P>
<P>
Ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) Chairman Yu Shyi-kun
signed a declaration proposed by the pro-independence Southern
Taiwan Society Monday, pledging to give birth to a new
constitution for Taiwan if he is elected president of the country
in the 2008 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Signatories of the Taiwan Future Convention declaration are
obliged to use all their power to promote the use of major local
dialects, including Southern Min, Hakka and aboriginal in
educational programs in middle and elementary schools, to
strengthen the curriculum  on Taiwan's history and literature  in
middle and elementary schools, and to comprehensively overhaul
the contents of textbooks for elementary students.
</P>
<P>
The signatories also have to recognize that the Republic of
China's sovereignty does not extend to China and promise not to
recognize academic degrees issued by universities in China during
the terms as president.
</P>
<P>
Yu also added a note to the convention saying that he will do his
utmost to change of the name of the country to "Taiwan Republic"
during his term as president, should he be elected to the post.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony,  held in the southern port city of
Kaohsiung, was witnessed by society chief Cheng Cheng-yu, who
revealed that the two DPP aspirants who have not yet signed, Vice
President Annette Lu and former Premier Frank Hsieh, have both
expressed their willingness to sign the convention.
</P>
<P>
Yu was the second aspirant to the DPP presidential nomination to
sign the declaration. Premier Su Tseng-chang signed the document
April 19.
</P>
